The second most significant event is probably the political process that started immediately after the genocide when the major political stakeholders put into place the broad national unity government of President Pasteur Bizimungu - it is extremely unusual in Africa for those with a major stake in a conflict to genuinely reunite and help bring back political stability to their country. Both of those events make Rwanda an exception in Africa. Let's talk about the country's prospects in the next 100 years.WIW: You have served as Rwanda's ambassador to the United Nations - what should the UN have done better or differently in 1994?MUGENZI: In the years from 1990 to 1994, the UN, both in its operating entities and in the Security Council, played a disastrous role in the lead-up to the genocide. The Unprep Commission and the Secretary General's special envoys were especially complicit because they had a major knowledge of the unfolding situation in Rwanda and, for reasons I cannot fully understand, they did not do enough. They failed to recognize the significance of the influx of weapons and armed uniformed former soldiers into Rwanda from Congo.
